INSERT INTO posts (id, title, slug, content, excerpt, images, post_type, status, metadata, published_at, created_at, updated_at, meta_title, meta_description)
VALUES (
  gen_random_uuid(),
  'How to Choose the Right Adult Foster Home in Hawaii',
  'how-to-choose-the-right-adult-foster-home-in-hawaii',
  $$<p>Finding the right care setting for a loved one is one of the most important decisions a family will ever make. In Hawaii, Adult Foster Homes (AFH) offer a uniquely personal alternative to larger assisted living or nursing facilities — and for many seniors, they provide exactly the warmth, safety, and individual attention that makes all the difference.</p>

<h2>What Is an Adult Foster Home?</h2>
<p>An Adult Foster Home is a private residence licensed by the Hawaii Department of Health to care for one to three adults who need assistance with daily living. The care provider — often a family — lives in the home alongside residents and provides personal care, meals, supervision, and a genuine sense of belonging. According to the Hawaii Department of Health, Adult Foster Homes must meet strict licensing standards covering health, safety, staffing, and resident rights.</p>

<h2>Why Choose an Adult Foster Home?</h2>
<p>Larger facilities can feel institutional and impersonal. AFHs offer a family-style environment that many seniors find far more comfortable. Key advantages include:</p>
<ul>
  <li><strong>Low caregiver-to-resident ratio:</strong> With only one to three residents, your loved one receives close, individualized attention every day.</li>
  <li><strong>Home-cooked meals:</strong> Many AFH providers prepare culturally familiar foods, which is especially meaningful in Hawaii's diverse communities.</li>
  <li><strong>Community and belonging:</strong> Residents often form genuine bonds with their care family, reducing isolation and loneliness.</li>
  <li><strong>Cost:</strong> AFHs are frequently more affordable than larger assisted living facilities, and many accept QUEST Integration, Hawaii's Medicaid managed care program.</li>
</ul>

<h2>Key Factors to Evaluate</h2>
<p>Not all Adult Foster Homes are the same. Here is what to look for when comparing your options:</p>
<ul>
  <li><strong>Licensing and inspection history:</strong> Verify the home's license is current with the Hawaii Department of Health. Ask whether there have been any citations or complaints.</li>
  <li><strong>Care level match:</strong> Make sure the home is equipped to handle your loved one's specific medical needs, mobility limitations, and cognitive status. Some AFHs specialize in dementia care.</li>
  <li><strong>Provider background and training:</strong> Ask about the primary caregiver's certifications, first aid training, and years of experience.</li>
  <li><strong>Location:</strong> Consider proximity to family, preferred physicians, and familiar community — whether that's Honolulu, Kailua, or a neighbor island community.</li>
  <li><strong>Cultural fit:</strong> Hawaii's multicultural communities mean that language, food, and cultural customs matter deeply. Look for a home where your loved one will feel at home.</li>
  <li><strong>Backup care plans:</strong> What happens when the primary caregiver is sick or needs time off? A quality AFH will have a documented plan.</li>
</ul>

<h2>Visiting Before You Decide</h2>
<p>Always visit in person — ideally more than once and at different times of day. Trust your instincts. Does the home feel clean and calm? Do current residents appear comfortable and engaged? Is the caregiver warm and communicative? These impressions matter as much as the paperwork.</p>

<h2>Financial Considerations</h2>
<p>Costs vary across the islands and depend on the level of care required. Some Adult Foster Homes in Hawaii accept QUEST Integration (Hawaii's Medicaid program), which can significantly reduce out-of-pocket expenses for qualifying families. Private pay rates typically range from roughly $2,500 to $5,000 per month depending on care complexity and location. Always get a written agreement covering all fees, services included, and discharge policies before moving in.</p>

<h2>Resources to Help You Choose</h2>
<p>The Aloha United Way's 211 helpline connects Hawaii families to senior care resources statewide. The Hawaii Executive Office on Aging (HEOA) also offers guidance on long-term care options and can help families understand what level of care is appropriate. EliteCareFinders.com maintains a directory of licensed Adult Foster Homes across Oahu and the neighbor islands to help you start your search.</p>

<p>Choosing the right Adult Foster Home takes time, but with the right questions and the right resources, you can find a setting where your loved one truly thrives.</p>$$,
  'Learn how to evaluate and choose the right Adult Foster Home in Hawaii for your senior loved one, including what to look for, questions to ask, and financial options like QUEST Integration.',
  ARRAY['https://images.unsplash.com/photo-1576765608535-5f04d1e3f289?auto=format&fit=crop&w=1200&q=80', 'https://images.unsplash.com/photo-1559839734-2b71ea197ec2?auto=format&fit=crop&w=1200&q=80'],
  'caregiver_resources',
  'published',
  '{}'::jsonb,
  NOW(),
  NOW(),
  NOW(),
  'How to Choose the Right Adult Foster Home in Hawaii | EliteCareFinders',
  'A practical guide to evaluating Adult Foster Homes in Hawaii — what to look for, questions to ask, and how QUEST Integration can help cover costs.'
);

INSERT INTO posts (id, title, slug, content, excerpt, images, post_type, status, metadata, published_at, created_at, updated_at, meta_title, meta_description)
VALUES (
  gen_random_uuid(),
  'Understanding Medicare, Medicaid, and QUEST Integration for Hawaii Families',
  'understanding-medicare-medicaid-quest-integration-hawaii',
  $$<p>Paying for senior care is one of the biggest concerns families face. In Hawaii, navigating Medicare, Medicaid, and the state's unique QUEST Integration program can feel overwhelming — but understanding how each works can open doors to care options you may not have known were available.</p>

<h2>Medicare: What It Does and Does Not Cover</h2>
<p>Medicare is a federal health insurance program primarily for adults 65 and older. It covers hospital stays, physician visits, some home health services, and short-term skilled nursing facility care following a qualifying hospital admission. However, Medicare does not cover long-term custodial care — meaning it will not pay for ongoing help with bathing, dressing, meals, or supervision in an Adult Foster Home or assisted living facility.</p>
<p>Many families are surprised to discover this gap. According to the Centers for Medicare &amp; Medicaid Services, Medicare covers skilled nursing facility care only for up to 100 days following a three-day hospital stay, and full coverage applies only to the first 20 days. After that, a significant daily copay kicks in, and coverage ends at day 100.</p>

<h2>Medicaid in Hawaii: QUEST Integration</h2>
<p>Medicaid is a joint federal-state program that provides health coverage for low-income individuals, including many seniors who have spent down their assets on medical care. In Hawaii, Medicaid is administered through <strong>QUEST Integration</strong> — a managed care program that covers a broad range of services, including long-term care for eligible individuals.</p>
<p>QUEST Integration is administered by the Hawaii Department of Human Services (DHS) through managed care organizations. Eligible seniors can receive coverage for:</p>
<ul>
  <li>Personal care services in the home or in a licensed care facility</li>
  <li>Adult Foster Home placement</li>
  <li>Nursing facility care</li>
  <li>Adult Day Health services</li>
  <li>Certain home and community-based waiver services</li>
</ul>
<p>Eligibility is based on both financial criteria (income and asset limits) and functional need (level of care required). Hawaii seniors who qualify for Supplemental Security Income (SSI) are generally automatically eligible for QUEST Integration.</p>

<h2>How to Apply for QUEST Integration</h2>
<p>Applications for QUEST Integration are submitted through the Hawaii Department of Human Services. Families can apply online at mybenefits.hawaii.gov, by mail, or in person at a local DHS office. A functional assessment will be conducted to determine the appropriate level of care. The process can take several weeks, so it is wise to begin the application as early as possible.</p>

<h2>Spend-Down and Asset Rules</h2>
<p>For married couples, Hawaii follows specific spousal impoverishment protections that allow a community spouse (the one not receiving care) to retain a portion of the couple's assets and income. Single applicants face stricter asset limits — generally $2,000 in countable assets. Certain assets, such as a primary residence (under specified equity limits), a vehicle, and personal belongings, are typically exempt. Consulting with a Hawaii elder law attorney before making financial decisions is strongly recommended.</p>

<h2>Long-Term Care Insurance</h2>
<p>For seniors who planned ahead, a long-term care insurance policy may help cover Adult Foster Home costs that neither Medicare nor Medicaid addresses. Policies vary widely in benefits and daily maximums, so review the policy documents carefully and contact the insurer early in the placement process.</p>

<h2>Getting Help</h2>
<p>The Hawaii Executive Office on Aging (HEOA) operates the Aging and Disability Resource Center (ADRC), which provides free counseling on Medicare, Medicaid, and long-term care options. The State Health Insurance Assistance Program (SHIP) — called the Hawaii SHIP — offers free, unbiased Medicare counseling to beneficiaries and their families. Both are excellent starting points for families trying to understand what coverage is available.</p>

<p>Understanding your options takes effort, but the right combination of Medicare, QUEST Integration, and other resources can make quality Adult Foster Home care in Hawaii financially achievable for many families.</p>$$,
  'A clear guide to Medicare, Medicaid, and Hawaii''s QUEST Integration program — what each covers, how to apply, and how they can help pay for Adult Foster Home care.',
  ARRAY['https://images.unsplash.com/photo-1450101499163-c8848c66ca85?auto=format&fit=crop&w=1200&q=80', 'https://images.unsplash.com/photo-1521791136064-7986c2920216?auto=format&fit=crop&w=1200&q=80'],
  'caregiver_resources',
  'published',
  '{}'::jsonb,
  NOW(),
  NOW(),
  NOW(),
  'Medicare, Medicaid & QUEST Integration for Hawaii Senior Care | EliteCareFinders',
  'Understand how Medicare, Medicaid, and Hawaii''s QUEST Integration program work together to help families pay for Adult Foster Home and senior care costs.'
);

INSERT INTO posts (id, title, slug, content, excerpt, images, post_type, status, metadata, published_at, created_at, updated_at, meta_title, meta_description)
VALUES (
  gen_random_uuid(),
  'Essential Questions to Ask When Touring a Senior Care Facility',
  'essential-questions-to-ask-when-touring-a-senior-care-facility',
  $$<p>Touring a senior care facility — whether an Adult Foster Home, assisted living community, or memory care unit — is a critical step in the placement process. Knowing what to ask can be the difference between a good fit and a costly mistake. Bring this list with you, take notes, and don't be afraid to ask follow-up questions.</p>

<h2>Before the Tour: Do Your Homework</h2>
<p>Before you set foot in the door, check the facility's licensing status with the Hawaii Department of Health. For Adult Foster Homes in Hawaii, you can request inspection reports and complaint history. Look up any formal complaints or enforcement actions. This background research will inform what to focus on during your visit.</p>

<h2>Questions About Staffing</h2>
<ul>
  <li>Who is the primary caregiver, and are they on-site around the clock?</li>
  <li>What happens when the primary caregiver is ill, on vacation, or has an emergency?</li>
  <li>What training, certifications, or licenses does the caregiving staff hold?</li>
  <li>Has the caregiver completed CPR and first aid training recently?</li>
  <li>For Adult Foster Homes: how long has the provider been licensed, and have there been any citations?</li>
</ul>

<h2>Questions About Daily Life and Care</h2>
<ul>
  <li>What does a typical day look like for a resident?</li>
  <li>How are meals prepared, and can the home accommodate dietary restrictions or cultural food preferences?</li>
  <li>What activities or social engagement opportunities are available?</li>
  <li>How are medications managed? Is the caregiver trained in medication administration?</li>
  <li>How does the facility handle medical emergencies? Which hospital or physician do they work with?</li>
  <li>What is the communication process for families — how often will you receive updates?</li>
</ul>

<h2>Questions About the Physical Environment</h2>
<ul>
  <li>Is the home or facility clean, well-lit, and free of hazards?</li>
  <li>Are bathrooms equipped with grab bars, non-slip surfaces, and accessible fixtures?</li>
  <li>Does the resident's room provide adequate privacy, storage, and personal space?</li>
  <li>Is there outdoor space for safe fresh air and sunlight — especially important in Hawaii's climate?</li>
  <li>How is the home secured to prevent wandering for residents with dementia?</li>
</ul>

<h2>Questions About Policies and Contracts</h2>
<ul>
  <li>What is the monthly cost, and what services are included?</li>
  <li>What additional charges might arise (incontinence supplies, transportation, special therapies)?</li>
  <li>What is the discharge policy if a resident's care needs increase beyond what the home can provide?</li>
  <li>Do you accept QUEST Integration (Hawaii Medicaid)? If so, what is the process?</li>
  <li>What is the notice period required for voluntary discharge or facility-initiated discharge?</li>
  <li>Can we review a sample resident agreement or contract before committing?</li>
</ul>

<h2>Questions to Ask Current Residents and Families</h2>
<p>If possible, speak briefly with a current resident or a family member of a resident. Ask open-ended questions like: "Has your loved one been happy here?" and "Is there anything you wish you had known before moving in?" Candid answers from people with firsthand experience are invaluable.</p>

<h2>Trust What You Observe</h2>
<p>Pay attention to the atmosphere during your visit. Are staff members and caregivers warm and attentive? Do residents appear relaxed and cared for? Is the home clean and does it smell fresh? Does the caregiver answer your questions openly, or do they seem guarded? Your gut reaction during a tour is often as informative as the answers you receive.</p>

<h2>Visit More Than Once</h2>
<p>Consider visiting at different times — once during a planned tour and once unannounced (if permitted). A meal time or early morning visit can reveal a lot about daily operations and quality of care.</p>

<p>Taking the time to ask thorough questions shows you are a careful advocate for your loved one — and the right care home will welcome that. A high-quality Adult Foster Home in Hawaii will be transparent, organized, and proud to answer every question on your list.</p>$$,
  'A comprehensive list of questions to ask when touring an Adult Foster Home or senior care facility in Hawaii, covering staffing, daily care, policies, and what to observe.',
  ARRAY['https://images.unsplash.com/photo-1582213782179-e0d53f98f2ca?auto=format&fit=crop&w=1200&q=80', 'https://images.unsplash.com/photo-1573497019940-1c28c88b4f3e?auto=format&fit=crop&w=1200&q=80'],
  'caregiver_resources',
  'published',
  '{}'::jsonb,
  NOW(),
  NOW(),
  NOW(),
  'Questions to Ask When Touring a Senior Care Facility in Hawaii | EliteCareFinders',
  'Know what to ask before choosing a senior care home. Our essential question list covers staffing, daily care, costs, and policies for Hawaii Adult Foster Homes.'
);

INSERT INTO posts (id, title, slug, content, excerpt, images, post_type, status, metadata, published_at, created_at, updated_at, meta_title, meta_description)
VALUES (
  gen_random_uuid(),
  'Legal Planning for Senior Care: Powers of Attorney, Healthcare Directives, and Living Wills',
  'legal-planning-senior-care-power-of-attorney-healthcare-directives-living-wills',
  $$<p>When a parent or loved one begins to need senior care, legal planning is one of the most important — and most often delayed — steps families can take. Having the right legal documents in place before a crisis occurs protects your loved one's wishes, simplifies care decisions, and prevents costly legal proceedings later. In Hawaii, several key documents form the foundation of solid senior care legal planning.</p>

<h2>Why Legal Planning Matters Now</h2>
<p>Many families wait until a medical emergency to address legal planning. By then, a loved one may no longer have the cognitive capacity to sign documents or express their wishes. Legal capacity — the ability to understand and voluntarily make decisions — must exist at the time documents are signed. Once capacity is lost, the only alternative is often a court-supervised guardianship or conservatorship, which is expensive, time-consuming, and emotionally draining for everyone involved.</p>

<h2>Durable Power of Attorney</h2>
<p>A Durable Power of Attorney (DPOA) is a legal document that designates a trusted person — called an agent or attorney-in-fact — to manage financial and legal affairs on behalf of the senior. "Durable" means it remains valid even if the person becomes incapacitated. Under Hawaii Revised Statutes Chapter 551E, a DPOA must be signed before a notary and, in some cases, witnesses.</p>
<p>Your agent can manage bank accounts, pay bills, manage real estate, and handle government benefits such as Social Security or QUEST Integration applications. Choose this person carefully — they will have significant authority over your loved one's financial life.</p>

<h2>Healthcare Power of Attorney (Healthcare Proxy)</h2>
<p>Separate from the financial DPOA, a Healthcare Power of Attorney designates someone to make medical decisions if your loved one cannot speak for themselves. This person — called a healthcare agent or proxy — can authorize or refuse treatments, select physicians and care facilities, and make end-of-life decisions based on the senior's known wishes. In Hawaii, this document is governed by Hawaii Revised Statutes Chapter 327E.</p>

<h2>Advance Healthcare Directive (Living Will)</h2>
<p>An Advance Healthcare Directive — commonly called a Living Will — is a written statement of a person's own medical wishes. It guides healthcare providers and family members when the person can no longer communicate. Common provisions address:</p>
<ul>
  <li>Use of life-sustaining treatment in terminal or vegetative conditions</li>
  <li>Artificial nutrition and hydration</li>
  <li>Resuscitation preferences (CPR)</li>
  <li>Pain management and comfort care priorities</li>
  <li>Organ and tissue donation</li>
</ul>
<p>Hawaii's Uniform Health-Care Decisions Act (HRS Chapter 327E) allows individuals to combine the healthcare proxy and living will into a single Advance Health-Care Directive document. The Hawaii Medical Association and Hawaii State Bar Association both provide sample forms.</p>

<h2>POLST: Physician Orders for Life-Sustaining Treatment</h2>
<p>For seniors who are already seriously ill or in a care facility, a POLST form (Physician Orders for Life-Sustaining Treatment) is a medical order — not just a directive — that travels with the patient across care settings. In Hawaii, the POLST form is bright pink for easy identification. It is signed by both the patient (or their surrogate) and a physician or advanced practice nurse. Unlike an Advance Directive, the POLST is immediately actionable by emergency responders and care staff.</p>

<h2>Guardianship and Conservatorship: A Last Resort</h2>
<p>If a senior becomes incapacitated without having signed the above documents, family members may need to petition the Hawaii Circuit Court for guardianship (over personal decisions) or conservatorship (over financial matters). These proceedings require legal counsel, court hearings, and ongoing court oversight. They can cost thousands of dollars and take months to resolve. This is why proactive planning is so important.</p>

<h2>Working with a Hawaii Elder Law Attorney</h2>
<p>Hawaii elder law attorneys specialize in estate planning, Medicaid planning, guardianship, and long-term care issues. Many offer free or reduced-cost initial consultations. The Hawaii State Bar Association's Lawyer Referral Service can connect families with a qualified attorney. If cost is a barrier, the Legal Aid Society of Hawaii provides free civil legal services to qualifying low-income seniors.</p>

<h2>Keep Documents Accessible</h2>
<p>Once documents are signed, keep originals in a secure but accessible location. Provide copies to your loved one's primary physician, the Adult Foster Home or care facility, and all named agents. Consider registering your Advance Directive with Hawaii's Advance Directive Registry through the Department of Health so it can be located quickly in an emergency.</p>

<p>Legal planning is an act of love. Taking the time to put these documents in place gives your loved one a voice in their own care — and gives your family clarity and peace of mind during one of life's most challenging chapters.</p>$$,
  'A plain-language guide to the legal documents every Hawaii family should have in place before placing a loved one in senior care — including power of attorney, healthcare directives, and POLST forms.',
  ARRAY['https://images.unsplash.com/photo-1589829545856-d10d557cf95f?auto=format&fit=crop&w=1200&q=80', 'https://images.unsplash.com/photo-1607863680198-23d4b2565df0?auto=format&fit=crop&w=1200&q=80'],
  'caregiver_resources',
  'published',
  '{}'::jsonb,
  NOW(),
  NOW(),
  NOW(),
  'Legal Planning for Senior Care in Hawaii: POA, Directives & Living Wills | EliteCareFinders',
  'Learn about powers of attorney, advance healthcare directives, living wills, and POLST forms — essential legal documents for Hawaii senior care planning.'
);

INSERT INTO posts (id, title, slug, content, excerpt, images, post_type, status, metadata, published_at, created_at, updated_at, meta_title, meta_description)
VALUES (
  gen_random_uuid(),
  'Navigating the Emotional Transition: Moving a Parent into Senior Care',
  'navigating-emotional-transition-moving-parent-into-senior-care',
  $$<p>The decision to move a parent into senior care is rarely simple. Even when it is clearly the right choice — when safety concerns are real, when caregiver burnout has set in, when medical needs have exceeded what home care can provide — the emotional weight of that transition can be profound. Grief, guilt, relief, and love can all exist at the same time. You are not alone in feeling all of it.</p>

<h2>Understanding the Emotions Involved</h2>
<p>Adult children often describe a deep sense of guilt when placing a parent in care, even when they have been providing exhausting levels of support for years. This guilt is almost universally reported and almost universally unwarranted. Making the decision to move a parent into a licensed care setting — including an Adult Foster Home in Hawaii — is often the most loving thing you can do.</p>
<p>Your parent may also experience a complex range of emotions: fear of losing independence, grief over leaving a familiar home, anxiety about new people and routines, and sometimes relief at having more support. Acknowledging all of these feelings — yours and theirs — is the first step toward a healthy transition.</p>

<h2>Before the Move: Preparing Your Parent</h2>
<p>Whenever cognitive ability allows, involve your parent in the decision-making process. Visit Adult Foster Homes together. Let them express preferences about location, cultural environment, food, and daily routines. Even small choices — which personal belongings to bring, which photos to hang — restore a sense of agency during a time that can feel disempowering.</p>
<p>Be honest but compassionate in your conversations. Avoid minimizing the change ("It'll be great, you'll love it!") or catastrophizing it. Acknowledge that this is hard, and that you are in it together. Frame the move around care and safety, not around what your parent can no longer do.</p>

<h2>The Day of the Move</h2>
<p>Plan the move carefully. Bring familiar items: a favorite blanket, family photos, a cherished plant, or a familiar scent. In Hawaii, many families bring leis and meaningful cultural items that create a sense of home. Keep the day low-key — avoid large gatherings that can feel overwhelming. If possible, stay for a meal or an activity to ease the initial separation.</p>
<p>It is normal for your parent to be upset or confused in the first days or weeks. This adjustment period does not mean you made the wrong decision. Adult Foster Home caregivers are experienced in this transition and can help your parent settle in at their own pace.</p>

<h2>After the Move: Staying Connected</h2>
<p>Your involvement does not end at move-in — it shifts. Regular visits, phone calls, and participating in activities are essential for your parent's emotional wellbeing and your own peace of mind. Hawaii's ohana culture places deep value on family bonds, and Adult Foster Homes often welcome family as part of the extended care community.</p>
<p>Communicate openly with the care provider. Share your parent's life history, preferences, routines, and things that comfort them when they are anxious. This information helps caregivers provide truly personalized care. Ask for regular updates, and speak up immediately if you have concerns.</p>

<h2>Managing Your Own Emotional Health</h2>
<p>Caregiver stress does not disappear after placement — it often transforms. Many adult children experience a complicated grief after a parent moves into care, mourning the parent they knew while also processing relief, exhaustion, and renewed worry. This is normal, and it deserves support.</p>
<ul>
  <li><strong>Join a caregiver support group.</strong> The Alzheimer's Association Hawaii Chapter and other local organizations offer groups for family caregivers navigating placement decisions.</li>
  <li><strong>Seek individual counseling.</strong> A therapist familiar with aging and caregiver issues can provide a safe space to process complex emotions.</li>
  <li><strong>Connect with other families.</strong> Talking to others who have been through similar transitions can reduce isolation and provide practical wisdom.</li>
  <li><strong>Give yourself permission to rest.</strong> You made a hard decision out of love. Accepting that you cannot do everything is not failure — it is wisdom.</li>
</ul>

<h2>When the Transition Is Difficult</h2>
<p>Some seniors refuse care altogether, insisting on remaining at home despite safety concerns. If your parent has cognitive capacity, you may have limited options without a legal guardianship. Work with their physician, social workers, and elder care specialists to explore every option. Hawaii's Adult Protective Services can be involved when there is a risk of self-neglect or abuse.</p>
<p>If your parent has dementia and is no longer able to understand the need for care, the transition can be especially difficult. The Alzheimer's Association offers guidance specifically for families moving a loved one with dementia into residential care, including scripts for difficult conversations and strategies for reducing distress on moving day.</p>

<h2>A New Chapter, Not an Ending</h2>
<p>Moving a parent into an Adult Foster Home or other senior care setting is not abandonment — it is an act of commitment to their safety, dignity, and quality of life. Many families find that after the initial adjustment period, their relationship with their parent actually improves. The burden of physical caregiving lifts, and what remains is love, presence, and connection.</p>
<p>Hawaii's Adult Foster Homes are built around the concept of ohana — family. In the best of them, your parent will not just be cared for. They will be welcomed.</p>$$,
  'A compassionate guide to the emotional challenges of moving a parent into senior care in Hawaii — including how to prepare, stay connected, and support yourself through the transition.',
  ARRAY['https://images.unsplash.com/photo-1573497019236-17f8177b81e8?auto=format&fit=crop&w=1200&q=80', 'https://images.unsplash.com/photo-1609220136736-443140cfeaa1?auto=format&fit=crop&w=1200&q=80'],
  'caregiver_resources',
  'published',
  '{}'::jsonb,
  NOW(),
  NOW(),
  NOW(),
  'Moving a Parent into Senior Care: Navigating the Emotional Transition | EliteCareFinders',
  'Practical and emotional guidance for Hawaii families moving a parent into an Adult Foster Home or senior care facility — from the decision through the adjustment period.'
);
